\begin_layout Standard
The Andes mountains are the most important geographical feature of Ecuador—and
 South-America— 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Insel2010"

\end_inset

.
 This mountain range crosses Ecuador from North to South.
 The Ecuadorian Andes comprises two flanks of mountains: the eastern and
 western ’Cordilleras’.
 Between these two flanks—that include active volcanoes—there are several
 inter-Andean valleys.
 Many of these Andean plateaus are over 3000 m above sea level.
 The steep elevations have an important effect on local climate.
 The lapse rate create the conditions for different Bio-climatic zones to
 exit.
 This enhances biodiversity.
 Yet, the original vegetation of the Andean valleys has almost disappeared.
 Most of the endemic vegetation was replaced by the Australian specie Eucalyptus
 globulus around 1860 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2012"

\end_inset

.
 Other introduced species are the Pinus radiata (from California) and the
 Pinus patula (from Mexico).
 This occurred for commercial reasons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Anchaluisa2013"

\end_inset

 with great ecological impact.
 Further, these species are prone to wildfires in the Andean dry season.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Climate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Tropical Andes climate has several drivers.
 The Amazon forest, oceanic currents, and the topography are among the main
 drivers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 The Amazon forest—through Evapo-transpiration—produces a great amount of
 water vapor.
 This water precipitates along the western Cordillera because of an orographic
 precipitation process.
 This precipitation is also produced in the eastern Cordillera.
 Air masses advected from the Pacific Ocean produce this effect.
 The influence of the Pacific Ocean in the climate variability is important.
 The Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) is the main driver of decadal climate
 variability in this region 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the inter-annual variability depends on the El Niño
 Southern Oscillation (ENSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vuille1999,Villacis2003,Martinez2011"

\end_inset

.
 These influences create several climate regions within the Andes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the Ecuadorian Andes—between 1500 to 3000 m—have a “Semi-Humid Mesotherm
al” climate (Pourrut 1995).
 Mean temperatures in this region range from 8 oc to 20 oc.
 Maximum temperatures span from 22 oC and 30 oC.
 Minimum temperatures range from -4 oc to 5 oC.
 Air masses from the Pacific Ocean and the Amazon region create three seasons
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pourrut1995"

\end_inset

.
 Two wet seasons during the periods February-May and October-November.
 A dry season spans from June to September.
 Total annual precipitation ranges from 800 mm to 1500 mm along the Andes.
 Relative humidity varies from 65 to 85 percent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fire
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wildfires mostly occur in three geographical regions of Ecuador.
 The Andean region has large extensions of introduced Eucalyptus forests
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Anchaluisa2013"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, the availability of fuels makes it the most wildfire-prone region.
 The fire season in the Ecuadorian Andes spans from July to November 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, the most critical months are July, August and September 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012,SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 The coast and the Galapagos Islands experience wildfire episodes from January
 to May 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wildfires produce severe impacts in Ecuador.
 Yet, information about these impacts is scarce and disperse.
 Wildfires produced 21.570 Ha of area burnt in Ecuador in 2012 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 The Metropolitan District of Quito (MDQ) is particularly vulnerable to
 wildfires.
 The vulnerability is high because 15.4 percent of the national population
 lives here.
 Additionally, vegetation covers 60.46 percent of its territory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Wildfires destroyed 2700 Ha of the MDQ vegetation in 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

.
 In 2012, the area burnt by wildfires increased to 4.882,16 Ha 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 This wildfire season cost the MDQ more than 50 million dollars 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, wildfires in Ecuador are anthropogenic in nature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, the MDQ reported that humans cause 95 percent of wildfires in
 the city 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Burning forests to convert them to agricultural use is the main cause of
 wildfires in the country 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013,Rodas2015"

\end_inset

.
 Forcing land use changes for urbanization purposes is another reason people
 start wildfires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Rural communities burn agricultural waste, which is a traditional practice
 that fosters wildfire occurrences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

.
 Rural people also burn regular waste because of the lack of waste management
 services 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, wildfires occur because of the damaging acts of arsonists 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Literature review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wildfires are a global phenomenon that produces severe impacts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luke1978,Conard1997,Morton2003"

\end_inset

.
 Catastrophic wildfire events claim lives 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haynes2008,Haynes2010"

\end_inset

, degrade the environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Shakesby1993,Stephens2004,Lane2010"

\end_inset

and destroy building infrastructure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morton2003,McAneney2009,Crompton2010"

\end_inset

.
 Wildfires also contribute to biodiversity loss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kodandapani2008,Pastro2011"

\end_inset

and affect the climate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conard1997"

\end_inset

.
 They are part of the natural evolution of vegetation ecosystems (HaynesBradstoc
k 2012).
 However, human actions amplify the impact over people, nature and infrastructur
e 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pausas2011"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, wildfires have a strong anthropogenic ignition pattern.
 In addition, population growth in rural areas increase human vulnerability
 to this hazard.
 The threat of wildfires have encouraged extensive research on the behavior
 of its precursors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Weather is one of the key components that contributes to wildfire activity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Powell1983,Williams1999,Mills2005,Haines,Mccaw2007,Dowdy2012,Engel2013"

\end_inset

.
 Wildfire weather refers to the meteorological influence over wildfires
 over a period of time —usually within days—.
 Common variables associated with wildfire weather are temperature, relative
 humidity, wind speed and precipitation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BoM2009"

\end_inset

.
 Each variable exerts influence in the liberation of water content in vegetation.
 This process—Evapotranspiration—controls the availability of fuels to be
 burnt.
 Most of the research conducted on wildfires and climate focuses on this
 daily approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roads2005"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, the study of wildfire predictability on a seasonal scale is also important.
 A key factor to explore this perspective is El Niño Southern-Oscillation
 (ENSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Swetnam1983,Simard1985,Kitzberger2002,Beckage2003,Wooster2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ENSO produces negative rainfall anomalies in some wildfire-prone regions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Swetnam1983,Simard1985,Kitzberger2002,Beckage2003,Wooster2012"

\end_inset

.
 The intensity of these anomalies depends on the regional influence of ENSO
 over climate.
 These rainfall deficits occur over the months before—and during–the wildfire
 season.
 ENSO’s influence may even increase by the superposition of the Inter-decadal
 Pacific Oscillation (IPO) (Verdon 2004).
 ENSO also has an influence over ignition patterns.
 In some regions it fosters the occurrence of lightning strikes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Beckage2003"

\end_inset

.
 These facts encourage the investigation of new studies of ENSO and wildfire
 weather around the world.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The west coast of South America is one of the regions most affected by ENSO.
 The coastal areas of Peru and Ecuador experience massive rainfall episodes
 during strong El Niño events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rodbell1999"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, there has not been enough research on its influence over other natural
 hazards.
 Wildfires occur all over South America 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Manta2008"

\end_inset

(Manta 2008).
 However, studies about wildfire weather in the northern Andean region are
 scarce.
 This study aims to describe the seasonal variability of wildfire weather
 in Ecuador.
 Also, we investigate if there is a link between this type of weather and
 ENSO in this region.
 This is important because wildfires occur every year in this country producing
 severe impacts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013,Rodas2015"

\end_inset

.
 A better understanding of wildfire weather variability and its precursors
 can provide useful information.
 These insights could be of special interest to emergency response services
 and planning authorities.
\end_layout

