\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study has investigated the variability of seasonal wildfire potential
 in Ecuador.
 The analysis included the examination of the relationship of wildfire weather
 and ENSO phases.
 Using a seasonal metric of wildfire potential—cumulative FFDI during the
 season July-August-September—, this study detected that five extreme seasons
 occurred during the period 1963-2012.
 An extreme season was defined as any year with a seasonal FFDI greater
 than the 90th percentile value.
 Most of these seasons—four out of five—occurred during diverse categories
 of El Niño strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The El Niño events in the Tropical Andes produce a below-average precipitation
 pattern 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Garreaud2009"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, this response is not uniform in the Ecuadorian Andes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Villacis2003"

\end_inset

.
 No relationship exists between ENSO and precipitation during the wet season
 (October-May) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Villacis2003"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, there is a consistent trend with below-average precipitation during
 the dry season (June-August) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Villacis2003"

\end_inset

.
 This may occur because precipitation has some Atlantic influence as well
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vuille1999"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, ENSO can largely explain the inter-annual variability of
 temperature (Vuille 2000).
 El Niño events are associated with higher temperatures in most of the Ecuadoria
n Andes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vuille1999"

\end_inset

.
 However, these studies relied on a relatively short period—approximately
 30 years—of weather station data.
 Moreover, they include only some wildfire variables —temperature and precipitat
ion—.
 In spite of this, they show a consistent agreement on the effect of El
 Niño over environmental conditions conducive to wildfires.
 This agrees with our overall results.
 Nevertheless, this should be carefully analyzed considering the use of
 reanalysis data in this study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general limitations of reanalysis data were discussed in the data and
 methods section.
 The results shown in Table 3 demonstrate that the precipitation produced
 by ENSO’s teleconnections is not well represented by the 20CR data.
 This variable should be strongly influenced by ENSO.
 Yet, the linear correlations do not show any link.
 This is an unexpected result especially for the dry season.
 The rest of the wildfire variables do show a statistically significant
 relationship with ENSO.
 In spite of the acknowledged biases in the data, the relationship is physically
 consistent.
 Yet, the coarse resolution of the reanalysis data brings uncertainty to
 the results.
 The quantification of these uncertainties is beyond the scope of this study.
 This could be accomplished examining each 20CR realization.
 An alternative approach could be the use of other reanalysis products.
 Although, the limitations may be similar.
 Another source of uncertainty is the selected wildfire index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI is an empirically designed index calibrated for southeast Australia.
 To our knowledge, this index has not being tested outside of Australia.
 The ecosystems of southeast Australia and the Ecuadorian Andes share the
 wildfire-prone Eucaliptus globulus vegetation.
 Yet, the particular characteristics of the Tropical Andean ecosystems may
 produce imprecise wildfire potential results.
 The computation of alternative indexes could provide a source of validation.
 The Canadian Forest Fire Weather Index (FWI) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanWagner1987"

\end_inset

has been used in several countries with positive results 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dowdy2009"

\end_inset

.
 Although computationally more complex to calculate, it could be interesting
 to test how well it represents fire weather in Ecuador compared to the
 FFDI.
 A future endeavor might be as well the design of an Ecuadorian Fire Weather
 Index System.
 Finally, another approach to strengthen this analysis would be the investigatio
n of ENSO’influence over wildfire activity rather than fire weather.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conclusding remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Roboust long-term wildfire activity records do not exist in Ecuador.
 The MDQ has started to produce more detailed information about wildfire
 impacts based on satellite data starting from the year 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

.
 However, the rest of the country lacks this information that would be valuable
 to evaluate ENSO’s influence over wildfires.
 For example, basic fire statistics such as the number of fire occurrences
 and area burnt per year would provide additional metrics to evaluate the
 impact of El Niño events over wildfires in Ecuador.
 Further investigation of ENSO’s influence over wildfires in Ecuador could
 enhance our capacity to anticipate these events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several studies agree that there is potential to use ENSO to forecast wildfire
 seasons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Simard1985,Nicholls2007,Wooster2012,Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, a predictive index has already been proposed for the Norhtern
 Patagonia region in Argentina 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kitzberger2002"

\end_inset

.
 However, as acknowledged by the author, the use of statistical-empirical
 methods to investigate seasonal wildfire predictability has limitations.
 For example, the assumption of stable ENSO phase’s relationships over a
 long period of time.
 Another important assumption to consider is the fixed timing of ENSO arrival.
 In spite of this, simple indices based on the relationship of ENSO and
 wildfire weather—or activity—can provide valuable information for decision
 makers.
 This information will facilitate timely decisions that can minimize economic
 impacts, protect the environment, and potentially save lives.
\end_layout

